-- Enrichment marathon batch: Cloudsmith, Cloudways, Clover, ClyoCloud, CMS Made Simple, CNCjs, Cockpit CMS, CockroachDB

-- ── Cloudsmith ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cloud-native artifact management platform for securely hosting, managing, and distributing software packages, containers, and AI models across the SDLC.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium (usage-based)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2016, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Belfast, Northern Ireland, United Kingdom$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cloudsmith Review 2026: Pricing, Features & Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cloudsmith is a cloud-native artifact management platform for secure package, container, and AI model distribution. Compare pricing, features, and reviews.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cloudsmith is a cloud-native artifact management platform that lets software teams host, manage, secure, and distribute packages, containers, and increasingly AI/ML models from a single control plane. It positions itself as a modern, SaaS-first alternative to self-hosted artifact repository managers such as JFrog Artifactory and Sonatype Nexus, and it supports essentially every major package format in use today, including npm, Docker/OCI, Maven, PyPI (Python), NuGet, Helm, Debian/APT, RPM/YUM, Conda, Cargo, Go modules, Ruby gems, Terraform modules, Vagrant boxes, and Cloudsmith's own generic and raw file formats. Because it is delivered as a fully managed cloud service with a global CDN, engineering teams do not need to run or scale their own artifact servers, patch storage infrastructure, or manage uptime for internal package feeds. Cloudsmith was founded in Belfast, Northern Ireland, in 2016 by Alan Carson (CEO) and Lee Skillen (CTO), two engineers who had previously worked on software supply-chain and DevOps tooling and identified a gap for a cloud-native, developer-friendly artifact repository that did not require the operational overhead of Artifactory-style on-premises deployments. The company has grown from a Belfast-based startup into a well-funded software supply chain security vendor with a global customer base, raising a Series A round (roughly $26 million combined across 2021 and 2023 tranches), a $23 million Series B led by TCV with participation from Insight Partners, and, in April 2026, a Series C round of approximately $72 million (reported in some regional coverage as €61.5 million), also led by TCV with Insight Partners participating. The Series C was explicitly framed around helping enterprises control and secure AI-driven software supply chains, reflecting Cloudsmith's expansion beyond traditional package management into securing the artifacts and models used to build and ship AI systems. Architecturally, Cloudsmith operates as a set of per-organization repositories, each of which can be public or private, and each of which supports fine-grained access control, single sign-on, audit logging, and policy-based governance (such as license and vulnerability policies that can block non-compliant packages from being promoted or consumed). A core differentiator is its 'single package, many formats' and 'single repository, many formats' flexibility: rather than provisioning a separate repository type for every package ecosystem, Cloudsmith repositories can typically hold multiple formats and expose native, protocol-compatible endpoints (so `npm install`, `pip install`, `docker pull`, `apt-get install`, and similar commands work unmodified against a Cloudsmith-hosted feed). The platform also emphasizes software supply chain security capabilities: vulnerability scanning, SBOM (software bill of materials) generation and ingestion, license compliance checks, provenance and integrity verification, and immutable, tamper-evident storage, all aimed at helping organizations meet emerging software supply chain security requirements (such as those driven by SLSA, executive orders on software security, and enterprise vendor risk assessments). Cloudsmith is closed-source, commercially licensed SaaS software; there is no self-hosted or open-source edition, though a generous free tier (called the Core plan) is available for open-source projects, small teams, and evaluation, offering a modest allotment of artifact storage and package delivery/bandwidth at no cost. Cloudsmith's pricing model is usage-based across two primary metered dimensions: artifact data storage, measured at a 'high watermark' (the peak amount of data stored, not cumulative uploads), and package delivery bandwidth (data downloaded/pulled from repositories); notably, uploads themselves are free and do not count against delivery usage. Paid plans reported in the market include a Team/Pro tier around $99-$149 per month with a defined storage and delivery allotment, a higher Ultra or Velocity tier around $299 per month with larger allotments, and custom Enterprise pricing for large organizations needing SSO/SAML, dedicated support, higher throughput, and compliance features; overage bandwidth beyond a plan's included allotment is billed at a per-GB rate (reported around $1.50/GB in some pricing breakdowns). Cloudsmith's target users are software engineering, DevOps, platform engineering, and security teams at companies of all sizes that need a private, centralized place to publish and consume internal packages and containers, mirror or proxy public registries (reducing exposure to upstream outages or supply chain attacks), and enforce governance over what dependencies are allowed into build pipelines. Its primary competitors include JFrog Artifactory (the long-standing market leader, generally self-hosted or hybrid), Sonatype Nexus Repository, GitHub Packages, GitLab Package Registry, AWS CodeArtifact, Google Artifact Registry, and Azure Artifacts, with Cloudsmith differentiating on being purpose-built as SaaS-first, broader native multi-format support without heavy configuration, and a stronger recent focus on AI/ML artifact and model governance as enterprises adopt AI-assisted development. Notable facts include Cloudsmith's origin as a bootstrapped Belfast startup that scaled into a venture-backed, globally used platform now valued in the context of a nine-figure cumulative funding total, and its positioning at the intersection of two fast-growing enterprise priorities: DevOps package management and software supply chain security in the age of AI-generated code and models. Cloudsmith's onboarding is designed to integrate with existing CI/CD pipelines with minimal friction, offering official integrations and documentation for GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Jenkins, CircleCI, and similar tooling, so teams can point their existing build pipelines at Cloudsmith repositories by changing a registry URL and credentials rather than rewriting pipeline logic. The company's engineering blog and changelog emphasize a fast, transparent release cadence, publishing detailed notes on new format support, security features, and pricing changes (such as the 'Building a Better Cloudsmith' pricing overhaul announcement), which is consistent with its developer-tool positioning and its effort to build trust with the security-conscious engineering teams it targets. As enterprises increasingly scrutinize the provenance of both traditional software dependencies and AI model weights/datasets used in production systems, Cloudsmith's roadmap has leaned further into being a control point for verifying what artifacts — code or AI models — are allowed to flow from development into production, a strategic bet reflected directly in how the company framed its 2026 Series C funding announcement.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'e47e77d6-8770-40cc-ad32-e7a099e5b0e2';

