-- ── Cloudways ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Managed cloud hosting platform that lets users deploy websites and apps on AWS, Google Cloud, DigitalOcean, Linode, or Vultr without server management.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription (pay-as-you-go)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$11/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2011, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Saint Julian's, Malta$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cloudways Review 2026: Pricing, Features & Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cloudways is a managed cloud hosting platform for WordPress, WooCommerce, and PHP apps. Compare pricing plans, features, and how it compares to rivals.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cloudways is a managed cloud hosting platform that removes the complexity of server administration by sitting between end users and major infrastructure providers — AWS, Google Cloud Platform, DigitalOcean, Linode, and Vultr — so customers can deploy WordPress, WooCommerce, Magento, and other PHP-based websites and applications on enterprise-grade cloud servers without needing sysadmin expertise. Rather than building its own data centers, Cloudways provisions and manages virtual servers on top of these underlying cloud providers, handling server setup, security hardening, caching, backups, monitoring, and scaling through its own management dashboard, effectively acting as a managed-hosting layer over commodity infrastructure-as-a-service. The company was founded in 2011 (some sources cite 2012) in Malta, where it remains headquartered in Saint Julian's, though it built much of its engineering and support organization out of Pakistan, giving it a distinctly global operating footprint from an early stage. Cloudways grew steadily as a bootstrapped and later investor-backed hosting company focused specifically on the PHP/WordPress ecosystem, building a reputation among agencies, freelance developers, and e-commerce store owners for combining cloud-level performance and flexibility with the simplicity of traditional managed WordPress hosts. In August 2022, DigitalOcean announced its acquisition of Cloudways for approximately $350 million in cash, with the deal closing in September 2022; Cloudways has continued to operate as a distinct, DigitalOcean-owned brand and product rather than being merged directly into DigitalOcean's core offering, preserving its multi-cloud support (including non-DigitalOcean providers like AWS and Google Cloud) even after the acquisition. Architecturally, Cloudways offers what it calls a 'Lightning Stack,' an NGINX-based web server configuration optimized for speed, paired with Varnish, Redis, and Memcached caching layers, Object Cache Pro integration for WooCommerce and WordPress, free SSL certificates via Let's Encrypt, one-click staging environments, and automated or on-demand backups. Customers choose an underlying cloud provider and server size (RAM, vCPU, storage, bandwidth) during signup, and Cloudways layers its own control panel, one-click app installers, team collaboration tools, and 24/7 support on top. In 2024-2026 the company introduced 'Cloudways Autonomous,' a higher-tier product line built around true autoscaling on Kubernetes for high-traffic WordPress, WooCommerce, and LMS sites, bundling Cloudflare Enterprise CDN, unmetered PHP workers, and free managed migrations — a response to the growing demand for hosting that can absorb traffic spikes (e.g., flash sales) without manual server resizing. Cloudways is closed-source, proprietary commercial software available only as a hosted service; there is no self-hosted or open-source edition. Its pricing follows a pay-as-you-go, hourly-billed model with no long-term contracts: standard 'Flexible' plans on DigitalOcean infrastructure start at $11/month (or roughly $8.25/month with an introductory discount) for a 1 GB RAM, 1 vCPU, 25 GB SSD, 1 TB bandwidth server, scaling up through mid-tier and large enterprise-class configurations priced per resource size, with equivalent tiers available on AWS, Google Cloud, Linode, and Vultr at correspondingly different price points reflecting each provider's underlying costs. The newer Autonomous plans are flat monthly tiers — Growth at roughly $99/month, Scale at roughly $199/month, and Plus at roughly $399/month — plus custom Enterprise pricing, each defined by baseline server counts, disk space, and bandwidth rather than raw cloud instance specs. Optional add-ons include Cloudflare Enterprise CDN, a Site Manager tool, malware protection, advanced 24/7/365 premium support, Rackspace-hosted email, and managed DNS. Cloudways primarily targets digital agencies, freelance developers, and e-commerce merchants who want AWS/Google Cloud-grade infrastructure and performance without hiring dedicated DevOps staff, positioning itself between fully self-managed cloud hosting (where customers configure raw EC2 or Droplet instances themselves) and fully managed, single-stack hosts like WP Engine or Kinsta that abstract away the underlying cloud entirely. Its direct competitors include WP Engine, Kinsta, SiteGround, Pressable, and Bluehost/Hostinger Cloud on the WordPress-hosting side, as well as more infrastructure-centric managed platforms like Servebolt and RunCloud; Cloudways differentiates through its multi-cloud choice (the ability to pick the underlying infrastructure provider) and its transparent, granular pay-as-you-go pricing. Notable facts include the $350 million DigitalOcean acquisition — one of the larger exits in the managed WordPress hosting space — and Cloudways' continued operation as an independently branded product line within DigitalOcean's broader portfolio, which now also includes complementary developer and cloud infrastructure tools. Cloudways' server management dashboard, historically built around its own custom control panel rather than a licensed third-party panel like cPanel or Plesk, gives users a simplified view of server-level settings (PHP version switching, application-level SSL, cron jobs, and firewall rules) alongside application-level tools, which is part of why the platform has been favored by developers who want more visibility and control than a fully abstracted host like Kinsta provides, without needing to SSH into a raw cloud instance for routine tasks. The platform also supports a team collaboration model with role-based access, letting agencies invite clients or team members with restricted permissions to specific applications or servers, and it maintains a marketplace of one-click application templates covering not just WordPress and WooCommerce but also Magento, Laravel, and custom PHP stacks. Since joining DigitalOcean, Cloudways has increasingly cross-sold DigitalOcean's own infrastructure and AI/developer tooling (reflected in the '4 free AI Copilot credits' now bundled into new signups), signaling a broader strategic integration between the two brands even as Cloudways retains its multi-cloud, hosting-agnostic positioning as its primary differentiator against DigitalOcean's own more developer-centric, unmanaged Droplet product line.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '4f36c751-0719-4122-8fe0-e1bd976404d2';

