-- ── Clover ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cloud-based point-of-sale and payments platform from Fiserv offering hardware, software, and merchant services for retail, restaurants, and service businesses.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription + hardware + transaction fees$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Starter plan; hardware sold separately)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2010, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$10,000+ employees (Fiserv)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Sunnyvale, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Spanish$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Clover POS Review 2026: Pricing, Plans & Hardware$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Clover is a Fiserv-owned point-of-sale platform for retail, restaurants, and services. Compare Clover's pricing plans, hardware, and transaction fees.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Clover is a cloud-based point-of-sale (POS) and integrated payments platform originally developed as an independent startup and now owned by Fiserv, one of the largest global payments and financial technology companies. Clover Network, Inc. was incorporated on October 15, 2010, and raised its initial $5.5 million round on November 1, 2010, led by Sutter Hill Ventures with participation from Andreessen Horowitz and angel investors; the company launched its cloud-based Android POS system in April 2012. Later that year, Clover was acquired by First Data Corporation, then the world's largest payment processor. First Data was itself acquired by Fiserv in a roughly $22 billion all-stock merger that closed on July 29, 2019, folding Clover into Fiserv's broader merchant-acquiring and payments business. Today Clover operates as Fiserv's flagship small-and-midsize-business (SMB) point-of-sale brand, distributed both directly and through a large network of bank and ISO (independent sales organization) partners who resell Clover hardware and processing services under their own branding. Clover's core proposition is an all-in-one, Android-based POS ecosystem: proprietary hardware devices (including the Clover Station, Clover Mini, Clover Flex handheld, Clover Go mobile card reader, and Clover Kiosk for self-service ordering) run a customized Android operating system and the Clover Dashboard software, which handles order taking, payment processing, inventory management, employee time tracking, customer engagement, and reporting. Because the platform runs on Android, Clover also supports a curated App Market of third-party integrations spanning accounting (QuickBooks), loyalty, online ordering, scheduling, and industry-specific tools, letting merchants extend the base POS with software tailored to retail, quick-service restaurants, full-service restaurants, and professional services. Clover is closed, proprietary hardware and software tightly bundled with Fiserv's payment processing; merchants cannot use Clover software without processing payments through Clover/Fiserv (or, in some cases, a reseller bank/ISO's processing relationship built on Fiserv's rails), which distinguishes it from software-only POS competitors. Pricing combines three layers: a monthly software subscription, one-time or financed hardware costs, and per-transaction processing fees. Clover's published general software plans include a Starter tier at $0/month (basic functionality with per-transaction fees), an Essentials tier around $29.95/month, and a Growth tier around $84.95-$89.95/month depending on business type, though pricing and plan names vary by industry vertical — retail plans have been advertised starting around $16/month, while restaurant-focused quick-service and full-service plans have started around $135/month and $179/month respectively, reflecting the more complex feature sets (table management, course timing, kitchen display integration) restaurants require. Transaction/processing fees for card-present sales typically range from about 2.3% to 2.6% plus $0.10 per transaction, while keyed-in (card-not-present) transactions run around 3.5% plus $0.10; because Clover is distributed through many reseller partners with negotiated rates, actual pricing a merchant receives can vary meaningfully depending on the ISO or bank relationship. Hardware bundles, especially in retail, are frequently sold with 36-month lease or contract commitments through resellers, which is a common point of criticism in merchant reviews, alongside concerns about cancellation fees and rate transparency that vary by reseller. Clover's target users are small and midsize brick-and-mortar and mobile businesses — independent retailers, cafes, restaurants, salons, and service businesses — that want a unified, easy-to-operate system for taking payments, running day-to-day operations, and getting basic business analytics without assembling separate POS, payments, and inventory tools. Its main competitors in the SMB POS space include Square (POS), Toast (restaurant-focused), Lightspeed, Shopify POS, TouchBistro, and other bank/processor-affiliated POS brands. Clover differentiates through its backing by Fiserv's massive processing infrastructure and its extensive bank/ISO distribution network, which gives it broad availability through merchants' existing banking relationships, though this same distributed reseller model means pricing and support quality can differ significantly depending on which partner a merchant signs up through — a nuance that is important for anyone comparing Clover pricing to more centrally operated competitors like Square or Toast. Beyond core payment processing, Clover has continued to expand its software ecosystem with capital and business-financing options for merchants (through Fiserv's broader financial services arm), gift card and loyalty program tooling, virtual terminal capabilities for phone and mail-order transactions, and analytics dashboards that let multi-location operators compare performance across sites from a single account. The Clover Dashboard web portal complements the in-store hardware, letting owners manage menus, pricing, employee permissions, and reporting remotely without needing to be on-site, which is particularly useful for multi-unit franchise operators and regional restaurant groups. Because Clover devices are Android-based, security and update management is handled centrally by Fiserv, with devices receiving OS-level and app-level updates automatically, reducing the PCI-compliance burden on individual merchants compared to older, less centrally managed terminal systems. Clover also supports EMV chip, contactless/NFC (including Apple Pay and Google Pay), and magnetic stripe payments across its hardware line, and its Kiosk product has become increasingly relevant for quick-service restaurants and retailers adopting self-ordering to reduce labor costs, a trend accelerated industry-wide in recent years. For prospective buyers, the most consequential decision is typically not which Clover plan to choose but which reseller or bank partner to sign up through, since two merchants with identical Clover hardware and software can end up with meaningfully different processing rates, contract lengths, and support experiences depending on their specific ISO relationship — a structural characteristic of Clover's go-to-market model that sets it apart from directly operated competitors like Square, Toast, and Shopify POS, where pricing is uniform regardless of which channel a merchant signs up through.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'e19def59-87a1-4c56-8c4c-42d792e37cfd';

