-- ── ClyoCloud ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Self-hosted personal cloud storage and media streaming server built with Nuxt, emphasizing privacy, file sharing, and a database-free architecture.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$ClyoCloud: Self-Hosted Personal Cloud Storage Server$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$ClyoCloud is a free, open-source, self-hosted personal cloud storage and media streaming server built with Nuxt. Learn about its features and setup.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$ClyoCloud is a small, open-source, self-hosted personal cloud storage and media streaming application built by the independent developer/organization WeeXnes. It is designed for individuals who want a private, self-controlled alternative to consumer cloud storage services like Google Drive or Dropbox, running entirely on the user's own hardware — a home server, a Raspberry Pi, a VPS, or a NAS — rather than on a third-party company's infrastructure. The project is hosted on WeeXnes's own self-managed OneDev instance at code.weexnes.dev/clyocloud rather than on a mainstream platform like GitHub, and it is also distributed through the Arch Linux User Repository (AUR) under the package names clyocloud and clyocloud-git, which makes it straightforward to install on Arch-based Linux distributions. The AUR package listing identifies WeeXnes as the maintainer and describes ClyoCloud as 'a sleek personal cloud storage and media streaming server built with Nuxt (stable version).' Because it is a small, community/solo-maintained project rather than a venture-backed company, there is no publicly documented founding year, company size, funding history, or corporate headquarters — it is best understood as an open-source software project rather than a commercial company, and any attempt to assign it conventional company metadata would be speculative. Technically, ClyoCloud is built on Nuxt 3 (the Vue.js meta-framework) for its frontend and uses Nitro/H3, Nuxt's built-in universal server engine, as its backend, which allows the entire application to be deployed as a single, relatively lightweight Node.js service rather than requiring a separate backend framework. Styling is handled with Tailwind CSS paired with the DaisyUI component library, giving the interface a clean, modern look without a heavy custom design system. Notably, ClyoCloud does not require a traditional database: instead of storing file metadata in PostgreSQL, MySQL, or SQLite, it uses sidecar '.cloudinfo' JSON files that travel alongside each stored file, meaning metadata (tags, descriptions, sharing settings) stays co-located with the actual file on disk. This design choice simplifies deployment and backup (copying the file directory preserves both content and metadata) at the cost of some of the query flexibility a real database would offer. Core features include drag-and-drop file uploads, bulk file operations, automatic thumbnail generation for images, video streaming support powered by ffmpeg for media transcoding/serving, a tagging and collections system for organizing files, public share links for sending files to people without accounts, and basic activity tracking. On the security side, ClyoCloud implements JSON Web Token (JWT)-based authentication, TOTP-based two-factor authentication (compatible with standard authenticator apps) that becomes mandatory once enabled for an account, and path validation logic intended to prevent directory traversal attacks against the file storage layer — a meaningful concern for any self-hosted file server that exposes a web-based file browser. The project is licensed under the GPL-3.0 (GNU General Public License version 3), meaning the source code is freely available to use, study, modify, and redistribute, and any distributed modified versions must remain open source under the same license; there is no commercial or hosted-SaaS version of ClyoCloud, no subscription tiers, and no vendor-controlled cloud offering — the entire value proposition rests on self-hosting. Because there is no paid tier, ClyoCloud's cost to a user is effectively the cost of the server/hardware it runs on (electricity, a Raspberry Pi or VPS, storage disks) rather than any software license fee. ClyoCloud's target users are privacy-conscious hobbyists, homelab enthusiasts, and self-hosting communities — the kind of audience found on platforms like the Arch User Repository, r/selfhosted, and similar communities — who prefer running their own infrastructure over trusting file storage to a third-party cloud provider. Within the crowded self-hosted file storage space, its closest comparators are more established open-source projects such as Nextcloud, ownCloud, Seafile, FileBrowser, and Immich (for photo/media-specific use cases); ClyoCloud differentiates from these larger, more feature-rich platforms by being deliberately lightweight, database-free, and narrowly scoped to file storage, sharing, and media streaming rather than the broader groupware/office-suite ambitions of Nextcloud. Given its scale as a solo or small-team open-source project rather than a funded company, prospective users should expect community-driven support (via its OneDev repository and any associated chat/forum channels) rather than commercial SLAs, and should evaluate it as an actively evolving hobby-to-production-grade project rather than an enterprise-ready platform. The choice to self-host the project's source repository on OneDev rather than GitHub or GitLab is itself notable within the self-hosting community: OneDev is a self-hosted Git server with built-in CI/CD, and WeeXnes running ClyoCloud's own development infrastructure on self-hosted tooling reflects the same underlying philosophy that motivates ClyoCloud's design as a product — reducing dependence on third-party platforms wherever practical. Deployment typically involves cloning or downloading the project, installing Node.js dependencies, configuring environment variables for JWT secrets and storage paths, and running the Nitro-based server process (optionally behind a reverse proxy like Nginx or Caddy for TLS termination in production), a workflow familiar to anyone who has deployed other modern Node.js/Nuxt applications. Because metadata lives alongside files on disk rather than in a centralized database, users migrating an existing ClyoCloud instance to new hardware can do so by simply copying the storage directory, which is a meaningful operational simplicity advantage for a hobbyist audience that may not want to manage database backups and restores as part of routine server maintenance.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '2a25838b-7398-4938-8fa5-7b5fcd9080f0';

