-- ── CMS Made Simple ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Free, open-source PHP content management system using the Smarty template engine, built for developers and site owners who need a lightweight, flexible CMS.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2004, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$Dutch$q$, $q$Italian$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CMS Made Simple Review 2026: Free Open-Source CMS$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CMS Made Simple is a free, open-source PHP content management system built on the Smarty template engine. See features, modules, and how it compares.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CMS Made Simple (commonly abbreviated CMSMS) is a free, open-source content management system first released in July 2004 under the GNU General Public License (GPL), a licensing model it has maintained continuously since launch. Built in PHP with MySQL as its database backend, CMS Made Simple's defining architectural choice is its use of the Smarty template engine, which strictly separates page content, site functionality (business logic), and visual templates into distinct layers. This separation was, at the time of the project's creation in the mid-2000s, a differentiating design decision aimed at letting designers and template authors work independently of the PHP code that drives functionality, and it remains the project's core technical identity today. The system has been continuously maintained and improved for two decades: in the summer of 2015 the project shipped version 2.0, described as a nearly complete overhaul of the underlying codebase and user experience, modernizing the platform after roughly a decade on its earlier architecture. In 2017, CMS Made Simple won the CMS Critic annual award for Best Open Source Content Management, recognition that reflected its continued relevance in a market that had, by that point, become heavily dominated by WordPress. The current stable releases are licensed under GPL-3.0 (earlier versions used GPLv2), and the project's source code, documentation, and downloads are distributed through its own website (cmsmadesimple.org), a GitHub organization (github.com/cmsmadesimple), and SourceForge, reflecting the multi-channel distribution common to long-running open-source projects. As a community-driven open-source project rather than a venture-backed company, CMS Made Simple has no formal founding-company metadata such as headquarters, employee count, or funding history in the conventional sense; it is maintained by a volunteer and contributor community rather than a single corporate entity, and its 'business model,' to the extent one exists, revolves around free core software plus an ecosystem of community-built modules, templates, and optional professional services from third-party developers and agencies familiar with the platform. Functionally, CMS Made Simple ships with a Content Manager for creating and editing pages in real time, a News module for article-based content such as blog posts or press releases, a File Manager for handling uploads and images, front-end and back-end Search modules, and a permissions-based Users manager that lets site owners control which backend users can edit which sections of a site. The default installation includes a lightweight WYSIWYG editor (historically MicroTiny, a streamlined version of TinyMCE) for non-technical content editors, while a large catalog of community-built modules — installable through an in-admin Module Manager — extends the base system with e-commerce, forms, image galleries, calendars, and other application-like functionality, allowing CMSMS to be used for more than simple brochure websites when needed. Because the Smarty-based template layer is fully decoupled from the PHP application logic, developers and designers can build highly customized front-end designs without needing to modify core PHP files, and the platform's API is described as extensive enough to support fairly complex custom development on top of the core CMS. CMS Made Simple's target users are website developers, freelance designers, small agencies, and technically inclined site owners who want a lightweight, template-flexible, self-hosted CMS with a smaller footprint and steeper design-control ceiling than out-of-the-box WordPress themes typically offer, without needing the more complex, code-heavy setup of a fully headless or enterprise CMS. Its most direct competitors in the open-source, self-hosted CMS space include WordPress (by far the dominant player), Joomla, Drupal, TYPO3, and newer flat-file or headless options like Grav, Statamic, and Decap CMS; CMS Made Simple differentiates primarily through its Smarty-driven separation of concerns and its long-standing reputation for stability and a lighter resource footprint compared to more feature-heavy competitors like Drupal. Notable facts include its 2017 CMS Critic award, its continuous GPL licensing since a 2004 launch that predates WordPress's dominance of the CMS market, and its status as one of the longer-running independent open-source CMS projects still actively maintained into the mid-2020s, having weathered two decades of shifting trends in web content management. CMS Made Simple's admin interface is organized around a traditional backend/frontend split familiar to anyone who has used a legacy PHP CMS: editors log into a secured admin area to manage pages, news articles, uploaded files, and users, while the public-facing site is rendered entirely through Smarty templates that pull structured content from the database at request time (with optional caching layers to keep performance reasonable on shared hosting). This traditional, monolithic architecture — as opposed to a modern headless or JAMstack approach — means CMSMS is best suited to conventional server-rendered websites rather than decoupled frontend/backend setups, which is an important distinction for anyone evaluating it against newer entrants in the CMS space. The project's installation requirements are modest: a standard LAMP or LEMP stack (Linux, Apache or Nginx, MySQL, PHP) is sufficient, making it compatible with a very wide range of shared, VPS, and dedicated hosting providers, and its resource footprint has historically been praised as lighter than Drupal's, which appeals to budget-conscious agencies hosting many small client sites on modest infrastructure. Community support channels include official forums, a wiki-style documentation site, and the GitHub issue tracker, through which bug reports, feature requests, and security patches are coordinated by the volunteer development team. While CMS Made Simple never achieved anywhere near WordPress's install-base or plugin ecosystem size, it has maintained a loyal niche following among developers who specifically value the Smarty-based separation of concerns and the predictability of a smaller, more tightly scoped core codebase over the sprawling, plugin-dependent complexity that can accumulate in larger CMS ecosystems.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '330370f7-f51f-46b8-a8a2-9d0d70a14749';

