-- ── CNCjs ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Free, open-source, web-based interface for controlling CNC machines running Grbl, Marlin, Smoothieware, TinyG, or g2core firmware from any browser.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CNCjs Review: Free Open-Source Web CNC Controller$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CNCjs is a free, open-source, web-based interface for CNC machines running Grbl, Marlin, Smoothieware, or TinyG. Learn features and how it works.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CNCjs is a free, open-source, web-based control interface for CNC (computer numerical control) machines, designed to run on low-cost hardware like a Raspberry Pi or a general-purpose laptop with Node.js installed. It acts as the bridge between a CNC controller board (typically an Arduino or Arduino-compatible board running firmware such as Grbl, Marlin, Smoothieware, TinyG, or g2core) and the operator, streaming G-code toolpaths to the machine over a serial connection — a USB serial port, a Bluetooth serial module, or a serial-to-WiFi module — and exposing a full control dashboard through any modern web browser. Because it runs as a lightweight server process rather than a native desktop application, CNCjs can be installed once on a Raspberry Pi mounted to or near the CNC machine, then controlled remotely from a phone, tablet, or laptop on the same network, which is a major convenience advantage over older desktop-only G-code senders that tie the operator to a single computer physically connected to the machine. The project is hosted on GitHub at github.com/cncjs/cncjs and is distributed as an open-source npm package under the MIT license, meaning it is free to use, modify, and redistribute, including in commercial products, with no royalty or licensing fee; there is no paid or enterprise tier, and the entire project is maintained through community contributions rather than a company. As with many hobbyist-to-prosumer open-source hardware tools, CNCjs does not have a conventional corporate history — no publicly documented founding year as a company, no funding rounds, and no formal headquarters — because it is fundamentally a community software project rather than a commercial entity, and it should be evaluated on that basis rather than assigned invented company metadata. Functionally, CNCjs provides real-time machine position visualization (including a 3D toolpath preview so operators can verify a G-code program before running it on physical material), a G-code sender/console for streaming and monitoring commands line by line, jogging controls for manually moving the machine's axes, workspace/coordinate system management, macro support for saving and replaying frequently used command sequences, and widgets for probe/tool-length setting, spindle/laser control, and grbl/Marlin-specific settings panels. Recent development has focused on expanding firmware and hardware compatibility: official support has been added for the CNC xPro V5 controller and for FluidNC, a Grbl-derived firmware that runs on ESP32 microcontrollers and communicates over WiFi rather than a wired serial connection, along with UART communication improvements that eliminate the need to reset the connection each time the interface is reopened, and new jog-cancel commands for both the Grbl and TinyG/G2 firmware families. The broader CNCjs ecosystem also includes companion projects such as cncjs-shopfloor-tablet, a simplified touch-optimized UI variant of CNCjs designed for tablets mounted on a workshop floor next to a running machine, and cncjs-controller, a client library that lets other applications communicate with a running CNCjs server over its event-based API, enabling custom integrations and automation scripts. CNCjs's target users are hobbyist and prosumer CNC machinists, makers, and small workshop operators who run desktop CNC routers, mills, laser cutters, or 3D printer-adjacent machines on open firmware like Grbl or Marlin, as well as more advanced users building custom shop-floor setups who need a lightweight, browser-accessible, network-controllable interface rather than a machine-tethered desktop app. Its closest comparators in the open-source G-code sender space include Universal Gcode Sender (UGS), bCNC, Candle, and LaserGRBL (more laser-focused), while on the higher end, commercial CAM/control suites like Carbide Motion (Carbide 3D) or Fusion 360's machine control integrations serve adjacent but more vertically integrated needs; CNCjs differentiates through its browser-based, network-accessible architecture, its broad multi-firmware support in a single tool, and its lightweight footprint suited to running unattended on a Raspberry Pi. Notable facts include its role as one of the most widely adopted open-source G-code streaming tools in the maker/CNC community, its continued active maintenance and firmware-compatibility expansion (including recent ESP32/FluidNC and WiFi-based controller support), and its permissive MIT license, which has allowed it to be bundled or referenced by hardware vendors and derivative shop-floor tools without licensing friction. Installation is handled through npm (Node Package Manager), with CNCjs distributed as a standard npm package that can be installed globally and launched from the command line with configurable options for listen port, host address, configuration file location, verbosity/logging level, static file mount points, and the specific controller type being targeted (Grbl, Marlin, Smoothie, TinyG, or g2core). This command-line-first distribution model reflects CNCjs's audience: technically comfortable makers and hobbyists who are already accustomed to flashing firmware onto microcontrollers and are comfortable with basic terminal usage, rather than a plug-and-play consumer audience. The web interface itself is a single-page application that communicates with the CNCjs server over WebSockets for real-time status updates, meaning the displayed machine position, work coordinates, and console output stay synchronized with the physical machine's actual state with minimal lag, which matters when an operator needs to react quickly to a probe touch-off or an unexpected collision. Because the project is entirely community-maintained on GitHub, its release cadence and roadmap are driven by contributor availability and pull requests rather than a formal corporate product roadmap, which is typical of mature hobbyist open-source infrastructure tools that have settled into a stable, incrementally improved state after their initial period of rapid feature growth.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'fae91cc1-45e7-4da3-9ef3-7c8d2bf1c7d8';

