-- ── Cockpit CMS ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Free, self-hosted, API-first headless CMS built for developers, offering flexible content modeling with no subscription and an MIT-licensed core.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2011, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Hamburg, Germany$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cockpit CMS Review 2026: Free Headless CMS for Developers$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cockpit is a free, self-hosted, API-first headless CMS with an MIT-licensed core. Compare features, self-hosting requirements, and use cases.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cockpit is a self-hosted, API-first headless content management system built by Agentejo, a product strategy, design, and development studio based in Hamburg, Germany. The project was first conceived in 2011, and Agentejo has held copyright over the codebase since 2015 under the MIT license, making Cockpit one of the longer-running independent headless CMS projects that predates the current wave of headless CMS platforms (which largely emerged and commercialized from roughly 2015 onward, such as Contentful, Sanity, and Strapi). Cockpit describes itself as a 'Sovereign Content Platform,' a positioning that emphasizes freedom from vendor lock-in: because it is open source, self-hosted, and free, teams that adopt Cockpit own their content infrastructure outright rather than depending on a SaaS vendor's uptime, pricing changes, or data-export policies. The core software is released under the MIT license and is explicitly marketed as 'forever free' with 'no subscription,' distinguishing it from most modern headless CMS competitors, which typically operate on usage-based or seat-based SaaS pricing with a limited free tier. Architecturally, Cockpit is an API-first CMS: content editors build structured content models (custom fields, relationships, repeatable groups) through an admin interface, and that content is exposed via REST and other APIs for consumption by any frontend technology, decoupling the content layer entirely from presentation. This makes it framework-agnostic by design — Cockpit explicitly supports being paired with Next.js, React, Vue, Node.js, PHP, and Ruby-based frontends, among others, letting developers choose their own rendering and delivery stack while using Cockpit purely as the structured content backend. Installation is designed to be fast and frictionless, with the project advertising a five-minute setup that requires no account creation or vendor sign-up, reinforcing its self-hosted, ownership-first philosophy. Feature-wise, Cockpit includes structured content modeling, asset/media management, webhooks for triggering external processes on content changes, component-based layout building, full-text search, form submission collection (useful for building contact forms or lead-capture flows without a separate service), localization/multi-language content support, audience personalization capabilities, content migration tooling, and page routing with SEO-oriented controls; more recently, the platform has added AI-powered enhancement features under an 'Autopilot' branding, reflecting the broader industry trend of headless CMS platforms integrating generative AI into content authoring and management workflows. Because Cockpit is self-hosted only, users are responsible for provisioning their own server environment (typically PHP-based, given the CMS's roots, though the ecosystem has evolved) and for their own scaling, backups, and security patching — the tradeoff Cockpit makes explicit in exchange for full data sovereignty and privacy compliance, which it highlights as particularly relevant for GDPR-sensitive deployments in Europe and for public-sector organizations that cannot use US-hosted SaaS content platforms. Cockpit's stated target audience spans several segments: individual creators and freelancers wanting faster project turnaround without recurring SaaS fees, marketers who need flexible cross-channel content distribution, developers who want an API-first, framework-agnostic, open-source content backend, agencies looking to avoid the recurring per-project SaaS costs and vendor lock-in that come with commercial headless CMS platforms, public-sector organizations with GDPR and data-residency requirements (Cockpit notes discounted pricing arrangements, such as 50% discounts, for qualifying nonprofits in contexts where paid add-ons or support exist), and enterprise teams that want to integrate a content layer into existing internal infrastructure rather than adopting a third-party SaaS dependency. Cockpit's direct competitors in the open-source, self-hosted headless CMS space include Strapi, Directus, Payload CMS, and KeystoneJS, while in the broader headless CMS category (including commercial SaaS options) it competes conceptually with Contentful, Sanity, Contentstack, and Storyblok, though Cockpit differentiates sharply from most of these by having no subscription cost at all for its core product, versus Strapi and Directus's open-core models (free self-hosted core plus paid cloud/enterprise tiers) or Contentful/Sanity/Storyblok's SaaS-first, usage-metered pricing. Notable facts include Cockpit's unusually long history for a headless CMS (tracing back to 2011, well before the term 'headless CMS' was in common industry use), its consistent commitment to a genuinely free MIT-licensed core rather than an open-core bait-and-switch model, and its origin from Agentejo, a boutique digital studio rather than a venture-funded software company, which shapes its lean, developer-first, no-nonsense product philosophy relative to more heavily marketed, investor-backed headless CMS competitors. Technically, Cockpit's admin interface lets content teams define custom 'collections' (structured content types with configurable field types such as text, rich text, media, relations, and repeatable groups) without writing code, while developers retain full control over how that content is queried and rendered through Cockpit's REST API endpoints, GraphQL-style querying in newer versions, or direct SDK integrations for popular frontend frameworks. The project's GitHub presence under the agentejo organization includes the core Cockpit repository alongside a range of official add-ons — such as a two-factor authentication module and internationalization (i18n) tooling — that extend the base installation without bloating the core, keeping installations lean for developers who only need a subset of functionality. Because Cockpit has no venture funding and no subscription revenue model to sustain a large engineering team, its release cadence and support responsiveness are shaped by Agentejo's capacity as a studio balancing client work with open-source maintenance, which is a tradeoff worth weighing against better-resourced, venture-backed alternatives for teams with mission-critical uptime or support-response requirements.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '26315baf-61aa-4fda-b2de-4986fe3babe9';

