-- ── CockroachDB ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Distributed SQL database built for resilience and horizontal scale, wire-compatible with PostgreSQL, available self-hosted or as a managed cloud service.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium / Usage-based$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2015, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York, New York, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CockroachDB Review 2026: Pricing, Features & Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CockroachDB is a distributed SQL database built for resilience and scale, PostgreSQL-compatible. Compare Basic, Standard, Advanced, and self-hosted pricing.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CockroachDB is a distributed SQL database management system built by Cockroach Labs, designed from the ground up to survive infrastructure failures — node outages, data center failures, even entire region failures — while maintaining strong consistency and continuous availability for transactional workloads. Its relational layer is built on top of a distributed, transactional, strongly consistent key-value store, and the SQL layer is wire-compatible with PostgreSQL, meaning applications can generally connect to CockroachDB using standard PostgreSQL drivers, ORMs, and tools, easing adoption for teams already working within the Postgres ecosystem. Cockroach Labs was founded in 2015 by Spencer Kimball (CEO), Peter Mattis (CTO), and Ben Darnell (Chief Architect), three former Google engineers who had worked on Google's internal distributed database systems, most notably Spanner, Google's own globally distributed SQL database; that lineage directly informed CockroachDB's design goals of surviving datacenter-level failures and scaling horizontally across regions while preserving ACID transaction guarantees, a combination that traditional single-node relational databases and many earlier NoSQL systems could not offer simultaneously. The company is headquartered in New York City and has raised substantial venture funding across nine rounds totaling over $800 million, including a $160 million Series E round and a $278 million Series F round led by Greenoaks that valued the company at approximately $5 billion, more than double its prior valuation — figures that place Cockroach Labs among the more heavily capitalized independent database infrastructure companies. Architecturally, CockroachDB automatically shards, replicates, and rebalances data across nodes and, optionally, across geographic regions, using the Raft consensus protocol to keep replicas in sync and automatically fail over without manual intervention when a node or region goes down; this multi-active availability model lets a cluster continue serving both reads and writes even during a regional outage, which is the core value proposition the product markets under the phrase 'always-on customer experiences.' The database also supports geo-partitioning, letting specific rows of data be pinned to specific geographic regions to satisfy data residency and latency requirements, which is particularly relevant for globally distributed applications subject to regulations like GDPR. CockroachDB's source code is publicly available and described as 'source-available' rather than strictly open source in the OSI sense; in August 2024 Cockroach Labs restructured its licensing so that companies with more than $10 million in annual revenue must pay a fee based on the number of CPU cores in the server systems where a self-hosted deployment runs, while startups and smaller companies below that revenue threshold can use the same enterprise-grade version at no cost — a shift that drew coverage (including from TechCrunch) as part of a broader industry trend of infrastructure vendors tightening license terms in response to cloud providers and larger competitors running their software without contributing back. Beyond self-hosted deployment, Cockroach Labs offers CockroachDB Cloud as a fully managed database-as-a-service (DBaaS) with three primary tiers: Basic, a pay-as-you-go, request-unit (RU) metered tier starting at $0/month with 50 million RUs and 10 GiB of storage included free each month, scaling to zero when idle and supporting bursty workloads up to roughly 30,000 RU/sec with 99.99% uptime across AWS and GCP; Standard, a newer (preview-stage as of recent releases) tier billed on provisioned compute starting around $0.18/hour for 2 vCPUs, aimed at steady, predictable workloads up to 200 vCPUs; and Advanced, the top cloud tier starting around $0.60/hour for 4 vCPUs, offering unlimited scaling, multi-region support across AWS, GCP, and Azure, up to 99.999% uptime, customer-managed encryption keys (CMEK), and compliance certifications relevant to HIPAA and PCI-DSS, targeting high-scale, security-sensitive enterprise applications. Cockroach Labs has also layered AI-oriented capabilities across its plans, including an MCP (Model Context Protocol) server, a ccloud command-line interface, agent skills, and distributed vector indexing, reflecting the database industry's broader push to support AI agent and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) workloads directly within the database layer. CockroachDB's target users span from startups needing a Postgres-compatible database that can scale without a costly re-architecture later, to large enterprises — reported customers include organizations like Equifax, Bose, and Comcast — running mission-critical, globally distributed, high-availability transactional systems in banking, retail, and media. Its principal competitors include Google Cloud Spanner (its closest conceptual relative, given the shared Spanner lineage), Amazon Aurora and Amazon DynamoDB, YugabyteDB (another PostgreSQL-compatible distributed SQL database with a similar value proposition), TiDB, and, at a broader level, traditional PostgreSQL and MySQL for teams that don't yet need horizontal, multi-region scale. CockroachDB differentiates through its combination of full ACID transactional SQL semantics, PostgreSQL wire compatibility, and true multi-region survivability, positioning it as a database that lets engineering teams avoid the classic tradeoff between relational consistency and horizontal, geo-distributed scale. Cockroach Labs also publishes CockroachDB Cloud's uptime and reliability guarantees prominently in its marketing, framing the product around 'always-on' resilience for consumer-facing applications where downtime translates directly into lost revenue or customer trust, a positioning aimed squarely at industries like financial services, e-commerce, and media streaming where transactional consistency and continuous availability are both non-negotiable. The company maintains an active open developer relations program, including detailed architecture documentation, a public roadmap, and a large body of technical content explaining distributed systems concepts like Raft consensus, MVCC (multi-version concurrency control), and geo-partitioning, which has helped CockroachDB build credibility among engineering teams evaluating distributed database options on technical merit rather than marketing alone. Migration tooling and compatibility layers are a recurring investment area, since the practical adoption path for most CockroachDB customers involves moving an existing PostgreSQL (or, less commonly, MySQL) application over time rather than building greenfield on CockroachDB from day one, and Cockroach Labs has continued to invest in tooling that reduces the friction and downtime associated with that migration path.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
